Here's an example code snippet for a simple web-based 3D model viewer using the Three.js library in JavaScript:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>3D Model Viewer</title>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <style>
      canvas {
        width: 100%;
        height: 100%;
        margin: 0;
        padding: 0;
      }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <script src="https://threejs.org/build/three.min.js"></script>
    <script src="https://threejs.org/examples/js/loaders/GLTFLoader.js"></script>
    <script>
      const scene = new THREE.Scene();
      const camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera(75, window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight, 0.1, 1000);
      const renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer();

      renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
      document.body.appendChild(renderer.domElement);

      const loader = new THREE.GLTFLoader();
      loader.load('model.gltf', function (gltf) {
        scene.add(gltf.scene);
      });

      camera.position.z = 5;

      function animate() {
        requestAnimationFrame(animate);
        renderer.render(scene, camera);
      }

      animate();
    </script>
  </body>
</html>
```
In this example, we're using the Three.js library to create a 3D scene, and we're loading a 3D model using the GLTFLoader. The `animate` function is called once per frame to render the scene. You can replace the `model.gltf` filename with your own 3D model file to load a different model. You can also customize the camera position and other settings to control the appearance of the 3D scene.

A code for property management and maintenance using 3D modeling tools could look like this:
```javascript
// Load 3D model of the property
const model = loadModel('property_model.obj');

// Define hotspots for areas of interest (e.g. plumbing, electrical, HVAC)
const hotspots = [
  { name: 'Plumbing', position: [10, 5, 5], radius: 1 },
  { name: 'Electrical', position: [2, 2, 10], radius: 1.5 },
  { name: 'HVAC', position: [-5, 5, -10], radius: 2 },
];

// Add hotspots to the model and attach event listeners
hotspots.forEach((hotspot) => {
  const sphere = createSphere(hotspot.radius);
  sphere.position.set(...hotspot.position);
  model.add(sphere);

  sphere.addEventListener('click', () => {
    showMaintenancePopup(hotspot);
  });
});

function showMaintenancePopup(hotspot) {
  // Use information about the hotspot to show a maintenance popup
  const popup = document.createElement('div');
  popup.innerHTML = `<h3>${hotspot.name} Maintenance</h3><p>There is a leak in the plumbing. Schedule repairs?</p><button>Schedule Repairs</button>`;
  popup.style.position = 'absolute';
  popup.style.top = '50%';
  popup.style.left = '50%';
  popup.style.transform = 'translate(-50%, -50%)';
  document.body.appendChild(popup);
}
```
This code loads a 3D model of a property and adds hotspots to the model for areas of interest, such as plumbing, electrical, and HVAC. When a user clicks on a hotspot, a maintenance popup is displayed with information about the issue and options for scheduling repairs. This can be a useful tool for property managers and maintenance personnel to identify and address issues in a property.

Here is an example code snippet using React to create a virtual staging tool for RealEstateMall:
```javascript
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import { useThree, useLoader } from 'react-three-fiber';
import { GLTFLoader } from 'three/examples/jsm/loaders/GLTFLoader';

const VirtualStaging = ({ modelPath, stagingItems, ...props }) => {
  const { camera } = useThree();
  const [activeItem, setActiveItem] = useState(0);

  const gltf = useLoader(GLTFLoader, modelPath);

  const handleItemClick = (index) => {
    setActiveItem(index);
  };

  const { nodes } = gltf.scene;
  const { materials } = nodes;

  const stagingItem = stagingItems[activeItem];

  return (
    <group {...props}>
      <primitive object={gltf.scene} />
      {stagingItems.map((item, index) => (
        <mesh key={index} position={[item.x, item.y, item.z]} onClick={() => handleItemClick(index)}>
          <boxBufferGeometry args={[item.width, item.height, item.depth]} />
          <meshStandardMaterial color={activeItem === index ? 'white' : 'grey'} />
        </mesh>
      ))}
      <mesh {...stagingItem} material={materials.virtualStaging} />
    </group>
  );
};

export default VirtualStaging;
```
This code imports React, along with the `useThree` and `useLoader` hooks from `react-three-fiber`, and the `GLTFLoader` from `three/examples/jsm/loaders/GLTFLoader`. The `VirtualStaging` component takes a `modelPath` prop, which is the path to the 3D model of the property, and a `stagingItems` prop, which is an array of objects representing the virtual staging items (furniture, decor, etc.).

The `useState` hook is used to keep track of the active virtual staging item, and the `useLoader` hook is used to load the 3D model.

The `handleItemClick` function is called when a virtual staging item is clicked, and sets the active item state.

The `nodes` and `materials` variables are used to access the nodes and materials of the 3D model, and the `stagingItem` variable is used to get the active virtual staging item.

The `group` and `primitive` components are used to render the 3D model and the virtual staging items, respectively. The `mesh` components are used to render the virtual staging items as boxes, and the active item is rendered as a mesh with the `virtualStaging` material.

This code can be customized to fit the specific needs and styling of the RealEstateMall website, and can be integrated with other tools and features to provide a seamless virtual staging experience for users.
